{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518972"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:08:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:08:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12966"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12966"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.4,0.1,0.34,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21263"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"547"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9604"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/36540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents with a two week history of a painless swelling on the right side of his neck. He has no other symptoms. His medical history includes a right hemicolectomy ten years previously for a Stage I adenocarcinoma. He has hypertension and takes perindopril. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks three to four cans of beer a day. Apart from signs suggestive of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, there is a well defined non-tender mass high in the anterior triangle of the neck (Image). Adjacent, several other smaller masses can be felt.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely primary source of his problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colon","Lung","Stomach","Tongue","Pancreas"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description of the mass and surrounding similar lesions fit for enlarged lymph nodes and in an adult in this age group, the assumption must be that they represent secondary malignant spread. Whilst a cancer at any of the listed sites might be responsible for such metastatic deposits, that the involved nodes are those in the upper cervical chain suggests that the primary site will be in the head or neck. With his history of heavy cigarette consumption, this patient would be at increased risk of not just lung cancer, but of malignant change within the oropharynx, most likely the \u003Cstrong\u003Etongue\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the patient is a smoker, increasing his risk to develop\u003Cstrong\u003E lung\u003C/strong\u003E cancer, he has no symptoms suggestive of a lung carcinoma. The nodes usually involved in lung carcinoma are those in the mediastinum (paratracheal, subcarinal, and hilar lymph nodes). More distal spread may involve the neck nodes, but more typically it is the supraclavicular (Virchow\u0027s node) rather than the cervical lymph nodes that are involved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELikewise, distal spread of \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric\u003C/strong\u003E tumours to the neck involve the supraclavicular nodes. Metastatic spread to the neck would be unusual for pancreatic and colonic cancers and again, spread would preferentially be to the supraclavicular nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Enlargement of nodes in the upper cervical chain suggests that the primary site will be in the head or neck."],"references":["Sakr M. Cervical: Lymphadenopathy. Head and Neck and Endocrine Surgery. 2016;163-190. Published 2016 Feb 9."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21263"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12966"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20038"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20038"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2420f151-cd81-4341-a78e-f7de58d7cc94.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2420f151-cd81-4341-a78e-f7de58d7cc94.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":394,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/21263"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-29T21:08:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-05-29T21:08:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5404"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"cr